One year ago, we were on our way back from Sudan. We were probably over some portion of the Atlantic Ocean either sleeping or reflecting on the mission we had only begun. 

I left you all at our last night in&nbsp;Sudan back in March. The next morning started early for me as I went out again to catch the sunrise. We soon were packed and loading into the vehicles to go to the airport in Yei. Once we were there, we slowly all said our goodbyes to all of our companions in Sudan. What I remember, it was very hard for me to board that plane. I felt like I would never share time with these people again. I hope this to not be true, but will always look upon our time together in a good light. On the plane back to Entebbe, I wrote down my final thoughts from the trip. I soon enjoyed watching the landscape below.

In Entebbe, we enjoyed a little bit of downtime and slowly eased ourselves back to the Western world. We met with the Bishop of the&nbsp;East Africa Conference shortly before we were to depart to the airport. He and David ended up seeing us off at the airport, as we made our way back to our Western worldly lives. 

Looking back is always dangerous. Time can romanticize experiences and other aspects of a trip of this nature. One thing I am truly thankful for is that the truth of the situations between all parties were not glossed over and our mission leaders were honest from the start. It would have been hard to find out a lot of the information that we knew and learned while on the trip after the fact. In all honesty, I think it would have marred the trip's mission for me, but instead, the honesty strengthened the purpose even more to me.&nbsp; 

In the last year in Sudan, free elections were held for the first time  in 24 years. Though controversy surrounded them the whole time, we can  see progression politically.&nbsp; 

As quickly as the trip came upon us, the trip ended. We soon began our lives again. Hopefully, we began them with a wiser sense of priorities, more worldly conscious view, and humbled hearts. Though we all catch ourselves caught up in our own lives from time to time, I think we can all agree that we can use our experiences to be better informed and make clearer choices for ourselves and the world.
